In 2006, it was added to the National Register of Historic Places due to its architectural and historical significance.

The 2013 FIBA Americas Championship was an international basketball competition held from August 31 to September 4, 2013 in San Juan, Puerto Rico. The tournament featured eight teams from North America, South America, and the Caribbean, who competed for a spot in the 2014 FIBA World Cup. The United States won the championship by defeating Mexico in the final match. This was the first major international basketball competition that the United States had participated in since winning the gold medal at the 2008 Beijing Olympics.

The Schengen Information System (SIS) is an important tool for security and border control within the European Union. It allows national law enforcement authorities to share information quickly and efficiently, in order to combat crime and terrorism more effectively. The SIS was established by the Schengen Convention in 1985 and became operational in 1995. It is based on a database that contains records of persons and objects wanted for arrest, missing persons, stolen vehicles, firearms, and explosives. The system also includes an alert mechanism to notify authorities when someone or something matches the criteria entered into it. The 2013 All-Ireland Senior Club Hurling Championship final was a hurling match that took place on March 17, 2013, at Croke Park in Dublin, Ireland. The game featured the Galway club Loughmore-Castleconnell and the Kilkenny club Ballyhale Shamrocks. Ballyhale Shamrocks emerged as the winners of the match with a score of 2–14 to 0–9. The victory also secured them a place in the 2014 All-Ireland Senior Club Hurling Championship final against Loughmore-Castleconnell.

A progressive dinner is an event where guests move from one location to another, enjoying different courses of a meal at each stop. The concept originated in the United States and has become popular for social gatherings, especially during the holiday season. 

The first course is typically served at the host's home or a designated starting point. From there, guests travel to the second location, where they enjoy the next course of the meal. This process continues until all courses have been enjoyed at each stop. The final destination is usually the most elaborate and festive location, with dessert being served as the last course.

Progressive dinners can be organized for various occasions, such as holidays, birthdays, or simply as a fun way to socialize with friends and family. They often involve themed decorations, costumes, and entertainment at each stop to create a unique experience for guests.

Fast cutting is a technique used in film editing to create a sense of urgency or excitement by rapidly switching between shots. This style can be seen in action films, thrillers, and other genres that aim to keep the audience engaged and on the edge of their seats. Fast cutting involves using short shot durations, often less than a second, to transition from one scene to another. The rapid pace of these cuts can make it difficult for viewers to process what they are seeing, adding to the overall intensity of the film. Some directors use fast cutting as a storytelling tool, while others may employ it simply for its visual appeal. Fast cutting is often contrasted with slow motion, which involves stretching out a shot's duration to create a sense of drama or suspense. Both techniques can be used effectively in different contexts, depending on the filmmaker's intent and the desired effect on the audience.
